tify when li is stricter, and read only TOML configurations. For CI without running servers, stub mode is essential.\n\nThe implementation will include:\n1. `http_exploit_toml.py` for TOML parsing and handling\n2. `exploit_http.py` with full functionality for expectation evaluation and comparison between nginx and li\n3. Integration of stub drivers that simulate responses for both servers\n4. Logic to detect and report when li enforces stricter expectations than nginx\n5. Validation of configurations through dry-run and stub execution\n6. Support for comparing outcomes across different languages using stub simulation\n\nThis approach ensures that the harness can validate behavior differences even without actual server instances, enabling comprehensive testing in continuous integration environments.\n\nThe exploit harness includes new stub drivers for Tier 5 benchmarks, such as leak_json_stub.py, leak_sse_stub.py, and leak_passthrough_stub.py, which simulate various exploit responses. A new Tier A exploit, duplicate_content_length, is added with corresponding TOML configuration and raw socket driver for comparing nginx and li behavior. The harness now supports running these Tier A tests in stub mode to validate behavior differences without actual servers, ensuring compatibility with CI environments. Updates to suite_exploits.toml may include adding Tier A to the pr profile subset or maintaining separate profiles for pr and nightly runs.\n\nThe exploit harness now supports all tiers, not just Tier G, with updates to scripts and documentation. A new script `scripts/check-tier5-exploit-harness.sh` and modifications to `httpd-plan-gates.sh` ensure proper exploit validation. Documentation updates include `docs/security-http-exploits.md` and release notes for the harness. The `defaults.toml` file will include default configurations for exploits, with values sourced from `exploits/<id>.toml`. The plan for exploit-harness is marked as completed, and the README has been updated accordingly.",
